<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 73, 92, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>1</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 125]]<|/det|>
Two particles \(P\) and \(Q\), of masses \(0.1 \mathrm{kg}\) and \(0.4 \mathrm{kg}\) respectively, are free to move on a smooth horizontal plane. Particle \(P\) is projected with speed \(4 \mathrm{m} \mathrm{s}^{- 1}\) towards \(Q\) which is stationary. After \(P\) and \(Q\) collide, the speeds of \(P\) and \(Q\) are equal.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 135, 635, 155]]<|/det|>
Find the two possible values of the speed of \(P\) after the collision.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 136, 920, 155]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 74, 92, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>2</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 140]]<|/det|>
A car of mass \(1500\mathrm{kg}\) is towing a trailer of mass \(m\mathrm{kg}\) along a straight horizontal road. The car and the trailer are connected by a tow-bar which is horizontal, light and rigid. There is a resistance force of \(F\mathrm{N}\) on the car and a resistance force of \(200\mathrm{N}\) on the trailer. The driving force of the car's engine is \(3200\mathrm{N}\), the acceleration of the car is \(1.25\mathrm{m}\mathrm{s}^{-2}\) and the tension in the tow-bar is \(300\mathrm{N}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 152, 432, 170]]<|/det|>
Find the value of \(m\) and the value of \(F\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 152, 920, 170]]<|/det|>
<mark>[4]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 73, 94, 92]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>image<|/ref|><|det|>[[356, 87, 677, 203]]<|/det|>


<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 222, 920, 290]]<|/det|>
A smooth ring \(R\) of mass \(0.2\mathrm{kg}\) is threaded on a light string \(ARB\). The ends of the string are attached to fixed points \(A\) and \(B\) with \(A\) vertically above \(B\). The string is taut and angle \(ABR = 90^{\circ}\). The angle between the part \(AR\) of the string and the vertical is \(60^{\circ}\). The ring is held in equilibrium by a force of magnitude \(X \mathrm{N}\), acting on the ring in a direction perpendicular to \(AR\) (see diagram).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 301, 544, 320]]<|/det|>
Calculate the tension in the string and the value of \(X\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 301, 920, 320]]<|/det|>
<mark>[5]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 75, 96, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>5</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 72, 920, 129]]<|/det|>
A particle starts from rest from a point \(O\) and moves in a straight line. The acceleration of the particle at time \(t\) s after leaving \(O\) is \(a \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 2}\), where \(a = k t^{\frac{1}{2}}\) for \(0 \leqslant t \leqslant 9\) and where \(k\) is a constant. The velocity of the particle at \(t = 9\) is \(1.8 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 141, 148, 160]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[160, 141, 308, 160]]<|/det|>
Show that \(k = 0.1\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 141, 920, 160]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 616, 728, 636]]<|/det|>
For \(t > 9\), the velocity \(\nu \mathrm{m} \mathrm{s}^{- 1}\) of the particle is given by \(\nu = 0.2(t - 9)^2 + 1.8\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 648, 148, 666]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 648, 920, 682]]<|/det|>
Show that the distance travelled in the first 9 seconds is one tenth of the distance travelled between \(t = 9\) and \(t = 18\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 664, 920, 682]]<|/det|>
<mark>[4]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 73, 92, 91]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 72, 920, 108]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 120, 920, 155]]<|/det|>
Find the greatest speed of the elevator and hence draw a velocity-time graph for the motion of the elevator.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 291, 920, 371]]<|/det|>
The diagram shows the vertical cross-section \(XYZ\) of a rough slide. The section \(YZ\) is a straight line of length \(2 \mathrm{~m}\) inclined at an angle of \(\alpha\) to the horizontal, where \(\sin \alpha = 0.28\). The section \(YZ\) is tangential to the curved section \(XY\) at \(Y\), and \(X\) is \(1.8 \mathrm{~m}\) above the level of \(Y\). A child of mass \(25 \mathrm{~kg}\) slides down the slide, starting from rest at \(X\). The work done by the child against the resistance force in moving from \(X\) to \(Y\) is \(50 \mathrm{~J}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 383, 146, 401]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[154, 383, 415, 401]]<|/det|>
